<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ920228-0045</DOCNO><DOCID>920228-0045.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- MCI Communications Corp.:   Firm to Offer Agencies   International Phone Services</HL><DATE>02/28/92</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A10</SO><CO>   MCIC</CO><MS>UTILITIES (UTI)</MS><IN>LONG DISTANCE TELEPHONE PROVIDERS (LDS)TELEPHONE SYSTEMS, INCLUDING CELLULAR (TLS)</IN><NS>GOVERNMENT CONTRACTS (GVC)</NS><GV>FEDERAL GOVERNMENT (FDL)</GV><RE>DISTRICT OF COLUMBIA (DC)NORTH AMERICA (NME)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   MCI Communications Corp. said it was awarded a two-yearcontract giving it the opportunity to offer federal agenciesinternational switched voice services.   Presently most agencies use American Telephone andamp; TelegraphCo. to carry their international phone calls. ATandamp;T competedfor the current contract.</LP><TEXT>   While an MCI spokesman estimated that the business couldgenerate up to $100 million in revenue over five years, theDefense Commercial Communications Office, which awarded thecontract, said the deal has an &quot;estimated lifetime value ofmore than $35 million.&quot;   Agencies could choose to continue service with theirpresent carrier. DECCO is the acquisition arm of the DefenseCommunications Agency and acted as administrator for federalagencies.   Services covered by the contract include private networkservice, calling card and operator service and billingfeatures. It also will give agencies more control over theirtelecommunications spending, MCI, based in Washington, said.   MCI had revenue of $8.43 billion in 1991.</TEXT></DOC>